5:
An air pocket? No need for an
oxygen tank this timeâ€”I suppose I
should consider myself lucky.
8:
It's quiet. Too quiet.
According to intel, the survey team
went off the grid somewhere around
here, yet...
12:
These should be the ruins the
mermaids were talking about, right?
15:
Monsters may be lurking nearby.
We'd best be cautious.
20:
They're definitely not part of the
survey team... but they also don't
strike me as looters. Who could they
be?
26:
Whoever you are, we know you're
there. Show yourself! We do not
mean you any harm.
30:
Lower your weapons. I am merely a
nautical archeologist charged with
investigating this area.
35:
My name is Eduardo. Who might you
be?
38:
I only ask because these ruins are
off-limits to the general
populaceâ€”at least, without a permit
from the government.
43:
He seems to be suspicious of us...
What should we do?
46:
Can't we just tell him the truth? Ah,
never mind, that wouldn't work...
50:
Exactly. "The mermaids asked us to
defeat a monster here" sounds like
something you'd make up on the
spot. He'll never believe us.
60:
A military dog tag? So this creature
was responsible for the
disappearances...
76: No, it was exactly what I needed!
86:
Alk! There's no need to pursue it
furtherâ€”our mission was just to
drive it away from the ruins.
89:
Now that it knows this area is not
safe, the creature is not likely to
return here.
93:
Thank you for your assistance. Are
you unharmed?
98:
Yes, but I'm afraid I can't say the
same for my ship. Now I won't be
able to return to the surface.
104:
Well, in that case, why not come
with us?
111:
Er, we didn't exactly come on a... You
know what? It's easier to show
youâ€”but promise not to be too
surprised, okay?
115: Thank you! Have a safe trip back.
118:
A-anyway, I guess this is where we
say goodbye!
122:
Not so fast. What is the meaning of
all this? You can communicate with
mermaids?! Just what kind of power
do you wield?
126:
Actually, you remind me of the
Crimson Blades. I heard they've
begun to show their faces again for
the first time since their sudden
disappearance... The government is
still after themâ€”with little success.
129:
Their leader was said to be a drifter...
Perhaps not unlike all of you.
135:
...My apologies. Considering you just
saved me, I ought to be showing
you more respect.
139:
We might just as well ask the same
of you. You aren't really a mere
scholar, are you?
143:
You would be right. I'm a special
operative working on behalf of the
Gaean government. I mainly
handle... highly classified missions.
147:
I see... From that look on your face, 
I get the sense that part of your
mission is personal.
151: I suppose it's my turn to surprise you.
159:
I merely call it that as a matter of
convenience. The truth is, I know
next to nothing about the
phenomenon.
160:
I've found no explanation, whether
magical or alchemical, for its cause.
164:
Please, allow me to accompany you.
These powers you bear... I feel they
could aid me in my quest to unravel
the mysteries of this curse.
167:
I will, of course, endeavor to make
this a quid pro quo arrangement. 
I am an expert when it comes to
information, after all.
170:
If you help me with my objective, 
I will aid you on your journey.
175:
Which means... you won't rat us out
to the Gaean government?
180:
As I said, information is my
specialtyâ€”both procuring and
concealing it. But if that's not
enough, I can always offer more.
186:
You mean to say every light up
there is its own world?
188:
Then that which bestowed these
powers upon me at the bottom of
the sea... It, too, must be somewhere
up there.
191:
So this is your world... The wind
doesn't bear on it the scent of the
tideâ€”how novel.
